"flus can mix to become a new strain" (paraphrased) - for anyone who doesn't know, the flu viruses are so good at evading the immune system because they:

1) have very slippery genomes. They're purposely not very good at preventing errors occurring in their DNA. They purposely have really high error rates (especially in certain areas of the genome) in order to maximise their genetic diversity, therefore escaping detection by the immune system etc.

2) they engage in horizontal gene transfer (this is what she is mostly on about). The viruses have segmented genes, and can transfer genes between each other. This means if the virus is getting wrecked by the immune system, and one individual gets a mutation to evade it, then it can transfer that gene to other viruses. This means if one evades the immune system, it doesn't have to survive to become the individual every new one comes from (really hard to do as it's more likely they'll get annihilated before reaching enough numbers, e.g. due to coming into random contact with a molecule that damages it). This also makes it so the immune system has less time to figure out this new adaption.

3) Flu viruses can perform recombination. This is essentially a last ditch attempt by the virus when it knows it's in trouble. It just randomly scrambles parts of the genome at the gene level. 99% of the time this is fatal and the virus no longer functions. But sometimes it works and the new ordering has immunity to what the immune system learnt. It's really crazy, and really a "call in the airstrike on my position" type deal.

The flu virus family's evolutionary plan is essentially "I don't need no fancy deep exploit (e.g. like HIV) if I just keep changing myself so quickly that immune systems don't realise I'm actually the same virus! Well it kind of brings up the "is it really the same virus?". You could alternatively think of it like something that evolves fast it turns into a new species every several months.
